{"root cause occurrence datetime": "2021-03-09 12:10:25", "root cause component": "Tomcat01", "root cause reason": "```json
{
  "root_cause_service": "Tomcat01",
  "root_cause_datetime": "2021-03-09 12:10:25",
  "confidence": 0.9,
  "reasoning": "The alert on `apache01` appears to be a cascading symptom rather than the root cause, as its internal metrics and access logs were normal around the alert time. All `Tomcat` services (Tomcat01-04) are red and exhibit frequent `GC (Allocation Failure)` logs, with `Tomcat01` showing the earliest event at `2021-03-09 12:10:25`. This indicates significant memory pressure and performance degradation within the application tier.\n\nThe most striking anomaly is observed on `Redis01` (red) and `Redis02` (green), both reporting `rdb_changes_since_last_save` values exceeding 900 million and over 1 billion, respectively, by `13:08:00`. This metric counts the number of dataset changes since the last RDB save. Such exceptionally high values are highly anomalous and strongly suggest an extreme and unprecedented volume of write operations directed at the Redis cluster.\n\nThis excessive write load is originating from the application layer (Tomcats, MGs, IGs) and is overwhelming Redis. The propagation of the failure is as follows:\n1.  A change in the application logic (likely a recent deployment or configuration) on the Tomcat servers (and potentially MG/IG services) triggers a massive, unintended write storm to Redis.\n2.  Redis, particularly `Redis01`, struggles to cope with this immense change rate, even if its `used_memory_peak` is relatively low, leading to performance degradation or potential persistence issues, causing `Redis01` to be marked as red.\n3.  The application services (Tomcats, MGs) making these write requests experience increased latency when interacting with the overwhelmed Redis.\n4.  This increased latency causes application threads on the `Tomcat` instances to remain active longer, consuming more memory and leading to frequent `GC (Allocation Failure)` events, as observed across all Tomcats starting from `12:10:25` on `Tomcat01`.\n5.  `MG01`, `MG02`, and `IG02` being red, with `IG02` showing a recent JVM restart, further supports the hypothesis that these dependent application services are struggling due to the upstream Redis and application performance issues.\n6.  Ultimately, the performance degradation in the application layer impacts the frontend `apache01`, leading to its alert.\n\nThe `Tomcat` services are the "Patient Zero" as they host the application code that initiated the excessive Redis writes, with `Tomcat01` showing the earliest clear symptom of the resulting memory pressure.",
  "recommended_action": "Revert the last application deployment to the Tomcat cluster."
}
```"}
